@NODE overview "cnmp/--overview--"


                              The Big Picture
                              ===============
   CNetMultiPort(tm), hereafter referred to as CNMP, was borne of a need for
CNet 3.5 applications that require Multi-User/Multi-Port communication.  Over
the last couple years I have seen people asking for MUD-like capabilities for
CNet and I have never seen this call satisfied.  After about 6 months of
playing with the idea, I figured it was time to do something about it NOW.

   Development of CNMP began on or about 21-Apr-1995 and has been the number
1 priority as far as programming goes (with a small grace period in early May
due to a family tragedy).

   CNMP will be continuously updated as new features/capabilities are
suggested and development will continue through the CNet 3.5 series with
altercations made to assure the most efficient and task-friendly handling of
inter-port/process communications with applications stemming far beyond the
CNet PORT level.

   Already planned from MetalSoft are things such as sysop<->user real time
chat with a GadTools or BOOPSI (I've not decided which as of yet..) GUI for
the sysop side and a one-on-one split-screen chat. This is not to say that
others can't try their hand at projects like this. These are only examples to
show the average Sysop what to expect for the future, even on a package such
as 3.05c that doesn't have a hell of a lot of hope as far as MUDs and
applications that require inter-port/process communications. Just because I
am concentrating on Chat-style applications for examples does not mean that
CNMP is a dead end.

   Anything that requires multi-port communications are possible.  CNMP is
capable of signalling a port when there are Message Port Events, Timer Events
and Keyboard Events.  These events and their meanings, as well as how to check
for them, are discussed more indepth later.
 
 
@ENDNODE
@NODE usage "cnmp/--usage--"


                                Using CNMP
                                ==========
   CNetMultiPort is a link library that provides a very powerful set of
functions to the CNet application/Pfile/door programmer.  To use functions
in the CNMP link library, you must add certain variables to your "empty.c"
code and to your "SC" and "SLINK" commands.

What to #include in your source (.c) files
=========================================
   To use CNMP, the following #includes must be present in your source
file(s):

      #include <libraries/easyrexx.h>
      #include <cnmp/cnmp.h>
      #include <clib/cnmp_protos.h>


What variables need to be added to your source (.c) files
=========================================================
   To use CNMP, the following variables must be present in your source
file(s):

      /* see "Cluster members" for an explanation of this structure
       * and variables.
       */
      struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *MyCnmpCluster=NULL;
      BOOL PORTPERMISSION=FALSE;


      /* for Arexx support */
      char                RexxPortName[40];
      struct Library      *EasyRexxBase=NULL;
      struct ARexxContext *RexxContext=NULL;

      /* see "EasyRexx implementation" for Arexx details */
      struct ARexxCommandTable rxtbl[] =
         {
         /* rexx tagname, rexxcommand, argformat, userdata */
         };
      }; 


What initialization code needs to be added to your source (.c) files
==============================================================
   To use CNMP, the following code must be present in your source
file(s) IMMEDIATELY after CNet's initialization routines (see the included
test project CNMPConf.c for example placement/location of this code): 

      /*********************************************************************
       * Initialize the CNMP ports and structures that make CNMP possible
       * DO NOT CHANGE ANYTHING IN THIS SECTION OF CODE!!
       *
       * NOTE: YOU pick a "BasePortName" to use.  Try and keep it unique!
       *       MetalSoft will attempt to keep a list of baseport names used
       *       by registered CNMP users/developers.  To get a list, simply
       *       contact me using any of the methods outlined in the section
       *       describing registration procedures.
       */
      if( !(MyCnmpCluster = InitCNMP(z, "BasePortName", sizeof(struct @{"PortVars" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 17}))) )
         {
         GetOut("Could not create CNMP(tm) cluster\n", 0);
         }

      /* Create the Rexx port */
      if(EasyRexxBase=OpenLibrary(EASYREXXNAME, EASYREXXVERSION))
         {
         /* set the arexx port name to BasePortNameREXXn where n=port number */
         sprintf(RexxPortName, "%sREXX%d", MyCnmpCluster->CNMP_BASEPORT, z->InPort);
         RexxContext = AllocARexxContext(ER_Portname, RexxPortName,
                                         ER_CommandTable, rxtbl,
                                         TAG_DONE) ;
         }
      else
         {
         PutText("ERROR 504: arexx port not opened!\n");
         }
      /**********************************************************************
       * end of CNMP initalization. DO NOT CHANGE ANY CODE ABOVE THIS POINT *
       * or CNMP may behave strangely or cause software failures            *
       **********************************************************************/

@ENDNODE
@NODE input-output "cnmp/--input-output--"


                          I/O handling techniques
                          =======================
  To simplify matters, with CNMP, you basically send messages using
@{"SendCNMPMessage()" Link SendCNMPMessage()}, wait for messages using @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()}, get them using
@{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()} and dispose of them using @{"DisposeCNMPMsg()" Link DisposeCNMPMsg()}.

   While there are many methods that may be used to handle CNMP I/O, the
one that works best is to put HandleIO in a while{} loop.  CNMP requires
that you call the HandleIO function to receive input and output from other
CNMP Ports, for timeout messages from the timer.device, messages from ARexx
and, optionally, the keyboard of the current port.  The only stream that you
can get I/O from without calling HandleIO is the current port's keyboard
buffer. This allows you to still let a user enter input without having to weed
through messages from other ports/ARexx and the timer.device.

   HandleIO performs a number of duties to reduce the burden of MessagePort
handling (ie. you don't have to write your own message port handler/code)
You simply call HandleIO and it returns a bit battern of signals (flags)
relating to what type of event/message was received. (see CNMP's @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()}
AutoDocs for more information.

@ENDNODE
@NODE eventmasks "cnmp/--eventmasks--"


                 HandleIO/Message Bit-patterns/Event Masks
                 =========================================
   The bit pattern/mask returned by @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()} is the basis for CNMP messaging.
There are six types of Event Masks currently implemented and there is
provision in the "cluster" structure (see "CLUSTER" for more information) so
that, if desired, advanced programmers may add their own events.  The current
event types or masks are:

   @{"UserMsg_Event" Link UserMsg_Event}
   @{"UserKey_Event" Link UserKey_Event}
   @{"UserTimer_Event" Link UserTimer_Event}
   @{"Rexx_Event" Link Rexx_Event}
   @{"ReplyMsg_Event" Link ReplyMsg_Event}
   @{"UserBreak_Event" Link UserBreak_Event}

@ENDNODE
@NODE UserMsg_Event "cnmp/UserMsg_Event"


                    User Message Events (UserMsg_Event)
                    -----------------------------------
   @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()} returns the UserMsg_Event bit set if a User Message Event is
received.  A User Message event is a message that is received from a remote
CNMP.  In other words, a message that another port has sent to the port that
called HandleIO.  To get the message(s) received from remote port, you must
use the function @{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()}.

   A snippet of code to show the format:



   /* your basic HandleIO call */
   ReturnBits = HandleIO(ER_SIGNAL(RexxContext), MyCnmpCluster);
   if(ReturnBits & UserMsg_Event)
      {
      PutText("We received notification of a msg from a remote port\n");
      /* now get message using GetCNMPMsg() */
      }

   See also @{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()}, @{"DisposeCNMPMsg()" Link DisposeCNMPMsg()}, @{"FileUserMsg()" Link FileUserMsg()} and @{"FreeUserMsgs()" Link FreeUserMsgs()}

@ENDNODE
@NODE UserKey_Event "cnmp/UserKey_Event"


                      Keyboard Events (UserKey_Event)
                      -------------------------------
   @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()} returns the UserKey_Event bit set if a there are characters
waiting in the user's CNet keyboard buffer.

   A snippet of code to show the format:



   ReturnBits = HandleIO(ER_SIGNAL(RexxContext), MyCnmpCluster);
   if(ReturnBits & UserKey_Event)
      {
      /*
       * PutText("There are characters waiting in the user's keybuffer\n");
       *...now get the input using EnterLine() or OneKey()
       */
      }



   You can check for this condition (characters in keyboard buffer) yourself
with the following code:

      if(z->KB1 != z->KB2)
         {
         /*
          * characters are waiting in z->KBuff.  Use EnterLine(), OneKey()
          * or your own custom function(s) to get input.
          */
         }

There is a CNMP defined macro in CNMP.H called KEY_CHECK that does the check.
Simply use the code below if you wish to use the macro:

      if(KEY_CHECK)
         {
         /*
          * characters are waiting in z->KBuff.  Use EnterLine(), OneKey()
          * or your own custom function(s) to get input.
          */
         }

@ENDNODE
@NODE UserTimer_Event "cnmp/UserTimer_Event"


                   timer.device events (UserTimer_Event)
                   -------------------------------------
   A timer.device generated event occurs every 5/8 second while @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()}
is active.  This allows HandleIO to return even if no messages from
remote ports, arexx or keyboard are received.  This can be useful if you
have to do other processing while still waiting for other messages/events.

   A snippet of code to show the format:



   /* your basic HandleIO call */
   ReturnBits = HandleIO(ER_SIGNAL(RexxContext), MyCnmpCluster);
   if(ReturnBits & UserTimer_Event)
      {
      PutText("received timer event\n");
      /* No messages waiting. do other stuff that needs to be done */
      }

   See also @{"CleanupTimeout()" Link CleanupTimeout()} and @{"SetTimeout()" Link SetTimeout()}

@ENDNODE
@NODE Rexx_Event "cnmp/Rexx_Event"


                         ARexx Events (Rexx_Event)
                         -------------------------
   ARexx events are only available if you have added the #includes and
code that are outlined in the sections titled, "What to #include in your
source (.c) files," "What variables need to be added to your source
(.c) files" and, "What initialization code needs to be added to your source
(.c) files."
   If so, @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()} will return Rexx_Event is an Arexx message has been
received from an ARexx script file.

   A snippet of code to show the format:



   /* your basic HandleIO call */
   ReturnBits = HandleIO(ER_SIGNAL(RexxContext), MyCnmpCluster);
   if(ReturnBits & Rexx_Event)
      {
      PutText("received ARexx event\n");
      /* Call HandleRexx() to process ARexx messages */
      }

   See also @{"HandleRexx()" Link HandleRexx()}

@ENDNODE
@NODE ReplyMsg_Event "cnmp/ReplyMsg_Event"


                    NT_ReplyMsg Events (ReplyMsg_Event)
                    -----------------------------------
   Without going much into detail of the process of exec message handling,
NT_ReplyMsg is the type of message that is returned to an exec message
port when a remote port has receved and made its obligatory reply to that
message.  NT_ReplyMsg's must NOT be replied to or exec will produce an
"enforcer hit" due to replying to a message twice.  CNMP takes advantage
of NT_ReplyMsg by using it to notify CNMP that it should free the memory
allocated for it's exec Message.  This is all completely transparent to
you, the programmer, and the user.  When you receive a ReplyMsg_Event,
all you need do is call @{"DisposeCNMPMsg()" Link DisposeCNMPMsg()} with a pointer to the message
that was returned.

   A snippet of code to show the format is you wish to use this feature:



   /* your basic HandleIO call */
   ReturnBits = HandleIO(ER_SIGNAL(RexxContext), MyCnmpCluster);
   if(ReturnBits & ReplyMsg_Event)
      {
      /* get all waiting NT_REPLYMSG messages and dispose of them */
      while( (UserCNMPMsg=GetNTReplyMsg( -1, MyCnmpCluster  )) )
         {
         HandleNT_REPLYMSG(UserCNMPMsg);
         DisposeCNMPMsg(UserCNMPMsg, MyCnmpCluster);
         }
      }

@ENDNODE
@NODE UserBreak_Event "cnmp/UserBreak_Event"


                    User Break Event (UserBreak_Event)
                    ----------------------------------
   A User Break Event is received if a CTRL-C is received by a CNMP
process.  For example, if you do a "break 14" and process 14 is the
program/Pfile that uses CNMP, a User Break Event is generated at the CNMP
user port.  ArtM (Amiga Real Time Monitor) can also generate a user break
by selecting the CNMP process and pressing the BREAK button/gadget.  Under
most circumstances, you will simply call the cleanup function GetOut()
to abort the port process.  This flag is useful if you wish to sent remote
ports messages, for exmaple, to notify them that the current port has been
forced to exit due to an externally generated CTRL-C.

   A snippet of code to show the format:


   /* your basic HandleIO call */
   ReturnBits = HandleIO(ER_SIGNAL(RexxContext), MyCnmpCluster);
   if(ReturnBits & UserBreak_Event)
      {
      PutText("received user break (CTRL-C) event\n");
      }

@ENDNODE
@NODE messages "cnmp/--Messages--"


   Messages are sent to remote ports using the @{"SendCNMPMessage()" Link SendCNMPMessage()} function.
@{"SendCNMPMessage()" Link SendCNMPMessage()} accepts 5 arguments, one of them being a @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} structure.
(see the autodocs for SendCNMPMessage for the other arguments)  The CNMPMsg
structure is what contains the information sent to a remote port, the type
of message to send, the target port number (or "ALL" for all ports) etc,..
We have a pre-allocated CNMPMsg set up in our "CnmpCluster" that was
initialized in the @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()} sequence.  This is the CNMPMsg that you
will fill out for each message that you send to another port.  It's full
member name is cc_cnmpmsg or MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg if you have
declared your cluster as

   struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *MyCnmpCluster;

   (See "CnmpCluster" for more information on other CnmpCluster members)

To send a message to another port, you must fill this structure out as
follows: 

   1. set the FromPort member equal to the CNet port number of the port you
      are sending this message to.  Specify "ALL" for all ports.
      Currently, only a single port number or "ALL" are allowed. More
      detailed "range" parsing will be available in registered/future
      releases.

      Note that FromPort is type (char []) so you must use sprintf() to
      convert the integer to a string representation as follows:

         /* this example would send the completed message to port 3 */
         int PortNum;
         PortNum = 3
         sprintf(MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->FromPort, "%s", PortNum);

   2. Set the CNMP_Type to the type of message you are sending (see the
      section titled @{"--MsgTypes--" Link MsgTypes} for currently implemented
      CNMP_Types and for information on creating/defining your own CNMP_Types.

      Example:

      /* This would set the message type as CNMP_VARSINIT. */
      MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->CNMP_Type = CNMP_VARSINIT;

   3. Set the VarsX variable(s) that apply to your CNMP_Type.

      Basically, the VarsX members of the @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} structure are LONG
      data types (you may typecast them to other types if so needed)
      which undergo no memory Allocation/Freeing.  The @{"DataX" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} members,
      however, are different.  These are POINTERS to memory locations.
      Also present is a @{"DataXLen" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} for each DataX member.  If
      DataXLen == 0 then no memory Aloocation/freeing is performed.
      If DataXLen > 0 then memory is malloc()'d for DataX and
      then Free()'d when the message is returned (after the remote port
      is finished with it - all transparent to you and the user!)

      Example:

         MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1 = "f1";
         MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1Len=4;

      The above example sets Data1 equsal to the string f1 (plus the
      usual NULL character (\0) at the end, for string data.

      Data1Len, therefore, must be set to the length of the string
      which is four (4) including the NULL byte.  CNMP Will allocate 4 bytes
      of memory for the data, copy the string into the actual message packet
      that is sent to the remote port, and then send it.  When the message is
      returned with NT_ReplyMsg set, CNMP frees the memory that was allocated
      for that message - all transparent to you and the user.  Basically, You
      need only send messages using @{"SendCNMPMessage()" Link SendCNMPMessage()}, wait for messages using
      @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()}, read them using @{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()} and dispose of them using
      @{"DisposeCNMPMsg()" Link DisposeCNMPMsg()}.  More is required but that is basically CNMP summed up.

   4. Call the function @{"SendCNMPMessage()" Link SendCNMPMessage()} to tell CNMP to send the message to
      the specified remote port(s).


@ENDNODE
@NODE MsgTypes "cnmp/--MsgTypes--"


                             Defining MsgTypes
                          ======================
   Perhaps the most powerful feature of CNMP is its definable message types.
If you want your application to support a specific type of message, you
define it. CNMP has a handful of pre-defined message types.  These are:

   @{"CNMP_ADDPORT" Link CNMP_ADDPORT}
   @{"CNMP_REMOVEPORT" Link CNMP_REMOVEPORT}
   @{"CNMP_VARSINIT" Link CNMP_VARSINIT}
   @{"CNMP_VARSREMOVE" Link CNMP_VARSREMOVE}
   @{"CNMP_TEXTECHO" Link CNMP_TEXTECHO}
   @{"CNMP_WAITNOTIFY" Link CNMP_WAITNOTIFY}
   @{"CNMP_RESUMENOTIFY" Link CNMP_RESUMENOTIFY}
   @{"CNMP_REQUESTNOTIFY" Link CNMP_REQUESTNOTIFY}
   @{"CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM" Link CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM}
   @{"CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT" Link CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT}
   @{"CNMP_ENTRYREFUSE" Link CNMP_ENTRYREFUSE}
   @{"CNMP_FLUSHALL" Link CNMP_FLUSHALL}
   @{"CNMP_KICKPORT" Link CNMP_KICKPORT}
   @{"CNMP_DUMPUSER" Link CNMP_DUMPUSER}
   @{"CNMP_STATUS" Link CNMP_STATUS}

   See the autodoc entry for each specific type for more information.

   But you may define your own message types by inserting a #define command
   into your source (.c) file or the header (.h) file for your application.
   Please DO NOT put your new message type in @{"include:cnmp/cnmp.h" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 1} as it may get
   over-written by accident when you install updates to CNMP.

   Also, please be sure to start numbering your user-defined CNMP_Types
   at 500 for future compatibility.

      #define CNMP_MyNewMsgType 500

   This would define a new message type with an integer of 500.  When
   @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()} returns with the @{"UserMsg_Event" Link UserMsg_Event} bit set, you do a check to see
   if the message type received by the port is any of the (pre-defined AND
   user-defined) CNMP_Types supported.  This is done using a switch/case loop.
   To add your newly created CNMP_Type, simply insert the following code
   into the switch{} routine that handles your CNMP_types:

      case CNMP_MyNewMsgType:
         /* code to handle your new type is inserted here */
         break;

  See the section titled @{"--IOHandler--" Link IOHandler() for more information on the
switch/case handler.

@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_ADDPORT "cnmp/CNMP_ADDPORT"


   #defined as

   CNMP_ADDPORT 300

   function:  notify remote ports that another port has entered.
   arguments: set @{"Data1" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} = MyCnmpCluster->cc_myport->PortName

@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_REMOVEPORT "cnmp/CNMP_REMOVEPORT"


   #defined as

   CNMP_REMOVEPORT 301

   function:  notify remote ports to remove your port from their linked lists.
   arguments: @{"Data1" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} = PortName

@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_VARSINIT "cnmp/CNMP_VARSINIT"

   #defined as

   CNMP_VARSINIT  302
   
   function:  use this to setup shared variables between ports.
   arguments: Data3 = pointer to PortVar structure

   See also @{"CNMP_VARSREMOVE" Link CNMP_VARSREMOVE}

@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_VARSREMOVE "cnmp/CNMP_VARSREMOVE"

   #defined as

   CNMP_VARSREMOVE 303

   function:  notify remote port(s) to remove our variables from their
              remote port variable list(s)

   arguments: none.  Set all @{"DataX" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} and @{"VarX" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} variables to 0 or NULL.


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_TEXTECHO "cnmp/CNMP_TEXTECHO"

   #defined as

   CNMP_TEXTECHO 304

   function:  an OLM-type method of sending text to a remote port

   arguments: @{"Var1" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30}     = TRUE (1) for PRIVATE MSG,  FALSE (0) for NON-PRIVATE MSG)
              @{"Data1" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30}    = text/string to send
              Data1Len = size (in bytes) of the data in Data1
              Data3    = Handle of user that sent this message (NULL or
                         0 if not a user-sent message)


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_WAITNOTIFY "cnmp/CNMP_WAITNOTIFY"

   #defined as

   CNMP_WAITNOTIFY 306

   function:  notify the remote port not to process anymore msgs from our port
              until we send @{"CNMP_RESUMENOTIFY" Link CNMP_RESUMENOTIFY}
              this entails GETTING the message and storing it in the linked
              list but not to process any of them.

   arguments: none


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_RESUMENOTIFY "cnmp/CNMP_RESUMENOTIFY"

   #defined as

   CNMP_RESUMENOTIFY 307

   function:  message from remote port to resume processing of messages from
              that port.

   arguments: none

@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM "cnmp/CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM"

   #defined as

   CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM 309

   function:  remote port sends this CNMP_Type if it wants to ask another port
              if it is allowed to enter.

   arguments: none


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT "cnmp/CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT"

   #defined as

   CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT 310

   function:  Send to remote port to notify it that entry is allowed
              If @{"CNMP_REQUESTCONFIRM" Link CNMP_REQUESTCONFIRM} is sent and CNMP_PORTPERMIT is received
              as a reply, a @{"CNMP_ADDPORT" Link CNMP_ADDPORT} message should be sent next to tell
              the remote port to add this port to it's list

   arguments: none

   See also @{"CNMP_ADDPORT" Link CNMP_ADDPORT}


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_ENTRYREFUSE "cnmp/CNMP_ENTRYREFUSE"

   #defined as

   CNMP_ENTRYREFUSE 311

   function:   this message type is sent to a remote port that has requested
               confirmation of entry.  It is a message that notifies the
               remote port that is is not granted access to join/enter
               the shared set of message ports that make up the application.


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_FLUSHALL "cnmp/CNMP_FLUSHALL"

   #defined as

   CNMP_FLUSHALL 312

   function:  tells port(s) to clear/free all messages that have piled up
              ie. remote port is telling another port to call the function
              @{"FreeUserMsgs()" Link FreeUserMsgs()}

   arguments: none


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_KICKPORT "cnmp/CNMP_KICKPORT"

   #defined as

   CNMP_KICKPORT 313

   function:  forces port(s) to exit/quit
              this does NOT dump the user from the CNet port but exits the
              CNMP application/program.

   arguments: none


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_DUMPUSER "cnmp/CNMP_DUMPUSER"

   #defined as

   CNMP_DUMPUSER 314

   function:  force the user to exit from CNMP AND dump him/her from the CNet
              port.

   arguments: none


@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMP_STATUS "cnmp/CNMP_STATUS"

   #defined as

   CNMP_STATUS 315

   function:  send a status message to another port.  Status messages
              are usually just informative messages detailing program
              progress.


@ENDNODE
@NODE IOHandler() "cnmp/--IOHandler--"

                   Basic routine/code for CNMP handling
                   ====================================
   This is one method (but not the only) that can be used to get and
send CNMP messages from/to other ports.  Please read/check this section
over completely as there are MANY C comments that may be important to your
understanding of CNMP.  There are also code hints & tips throughout.  Most
of this code is exactly what is used in CNMPConf, a small user conference
replacement that I wrote to aid in CNMP developement:

   /* Main event loop */
   /* flush keyboard buffer */
   KBFlush(z);
   while(!done)
     {
     MsgMask = HandleIO(ER_SIGNAL(RexxContext), MyCnmpCluster );
     CheckFlowControl(); /* forces CNEt to update it's keyboard buffers */

     if(!CarrierCheck(z)) /* carrier check routine */
       {
       GetOut("", 0);
       }

     /*
      * Check message port events first - they have priority because
      * they must be processed ASAP!  (ie. the remote port may not be
      * present/available later.  This is of no consequence code-wise
      * but the port may not receive your reply message (if you send
      * one) later.
      *
      * ADDPORT events are user notifiable/permissible and if you wish to be
      * notified of a port's intent to enter and have control over it set
      * PORTPERMISSION=1 or PORTPERMISSION=TRUE.
      * PORTPERMISSION==1 causes CNMP(tm) to send a @{"CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM" Link CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM}
      * to all available CNMP(tm) ports on entry.
      *
      * Sending a @{"CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT" Link CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT} in reply will
      * allow the remote port to converse with the current port and share
      * data between them. The port will only be allowed to converse with
      * ports that have sent CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT in reply.  All other ports
      * will act as if that port does not exist and those ports will not be
      * seen by the port that requested permission.
      *
      * It is possible to alter the @{"CNMP_ADDPORT" Link CNMP_ADDPORT} message check to function
      * in this manner also..  All you need do is do your permission check
      * before you call @{"CNMPortToList()" Link CNMPortToList()}.
      *
      * When the you are finished with a message, you
      * should call DisposeCNMPMessage() to let
      * us take care of freeing and disposal of it.
      * messages that are not "disposed" will pile up and
      * eat memory.  ALL messages are cleaned up on exit
      * as a precautionary measure but PLEASE do not rely
      * on this feature as it is ignorant of systems that
      * may have very little RAM to spare
      * also note that messages WILL be lost if the system
      * runs low on memory.  There is no way around this
      * except to send the message CNMP_FREEALL to all
      * ports.  CNMP_FREEALL causes all ports to flush
      * their message lists.  Please use this message type
      * sparingly as any queued messages are
      * deleted/removed before they are user processed thus causing
      * them to be purged without the interpreter processing them.
      *
      * types CNMP_ADDPORT, CNMP_REMOVEPORT, CNMP_VARSINIT,
      * and @{"CNMP_VARSREMOVE" Link CNMP_VARSREMOVE} are not affected by this at the
      * @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()} level.  In other words, @{"CNMP_FLUSHALL" Link CNMP_FLUSHALL}
      * affects messages that would have been returned to you
      * via @{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()}.
      * it should be also noted that a port can be "removed"
      * at any time so ports should ALWAYS be checked
      * for validity before sending messages or accessing
      * remote port data.  This can be done using the
      * @{"PortFromMsg()" Link PortFromMsg()} or @{"PortFromNum()" Link PortFromNum()} or @{"CheckCNMPExists()" Link CheckCNMPExists()}
      * functions.  I recommend using @{"CheckCNMPExists()" Link CheckCNMPExists()} as it
      * checks to see if the actual **Exec** MsgPort exists whereas
      * PortFromMsg() and PortFromNum() check only at the level
      * of the current port's linked list which may not be valid
      * 100% of the time.  The validity of these two functions
      * is directly related to the amount of time that has passed
      * between your calls to @{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()}.   If you wait long
      * periods of time between @{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()} calls, then you are
      * sacrificing  the validity of your port lists.  The REMOTE ports may
      * go away before all messages have been handled.  This doesn't affect
      * your port message list but the remote port that send the message may
      * have already exited/quit and may not be present to receive a reply
      * (if you send one).
      */

     /*
      * we should check @{"ReplyMsg_Event" Link ReplyMsg_Event}s and @{"UserMsg_Event" Link UserMsg_Event}s first!  This frees
      * RAM and also speeds up the message server by shortening the queued
      * message list.
      */

     if(MsgMask & ReplyMsg_Event)
       {
       /* get NT_REPLYMSG from any and all ports and handle them */
       while((UserCNMPMsg=GetNTReplyMsg( -1, MyCnmpCluster  )))
          {
          HandleNT_REPLYMSG(UserCNMPMsg);
          DisposeCNMPMsg(UserCNMPMsg, MyCnmpCluster);
          }
       }
     if(MsgMask & Rexx_Event)
       {
       /* An arexx event/msg was sent to us.. Handle it.. */
       @{"HandleRexx()" Link HandleRexx()};
       }
     if(MsgMask & UserBreak_Event)
       {
       /* received CTRL-C */
       GetOut("^C", 0);
       }
     if(MsgMask & @{"UserMsg_Event" Link UserMsg_Event})
       {
       /*
        * There is a remote message waiting at our message port.
        * use @{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()} to get them one at a time.
        * use @{"DisposeCNMPMsg()" Link DisposeCNMPMsg()} to clean the msg up after used.
        */

       while((UserCNMPMsg=GetCNMPMsg( -1, MyCnmpCluster )))
         {
         switch(UserCNMPMsg->CNMP_Type)
           {
           case @{"CNMP_ADDPORT" Link CNMP_ADDPORT}:
             /*
              * Check if this message holds a NEW port to be added
              * We could also do checking on the port/user to see if
              * entry is allowed.
              * if you want to refuse a user entry, simply do not call
              * @{"CNMPortToList()" Link CNMPortToList()}.  If you call
              * CNMPortToList(), his port is added to your list of ports
              * and your port is added to his.
              */

             sprintf(OtherPortName, "%s%d",
                                           MyCnmpCluster->CNMP_BASEPORT,
                                           UserCNMPMsg->FromPort);

             CNMPortToList(MyCnmpCluster, UserCNMPMsg->FromPort,
                                                         OtherPortName);
             break;

           case @{"CNMP_REMOVEPORT" Link CNMP_REMOVEPORT}:
             /* we have been notified that a remote port has exited.
              * CNMP takes care of removing the port from it's lists
              * so all we need do is clean up our application specific
              * data for that port.  The port number is held in the
              * variable "FromPort" in the @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} structure.
              */

             sprintf(z->ABuffer, "port %d has exited\n",
                                                 UserCNMPMsg->FromPort);
             PutA();
             break;

           case @{"CNMP_KICKPORT" Link CNMP_KICKPORT}:
             /* This port has been given the boot by a remote port */
             sprintf(z->ABuffer, "You have been kicked by port %d!\n",
                                                 UserCNMPMsg->FromPort);
             PutA();

             /* We free all messages now, before exiting, just in case */
             FreeUserMsgs(MyCnmpCluster);

             /* disable any further messages from being received. */
             MyCnmpCluster->cc_ignoremsgs=TRUE;

             done = TRUE;
             break;

           case @{"CNMP_STATUS" Link CNMP_STATUS}:
             /* user implemented - simply a status message */
             sprintf(z->ABuffer, "<Status> %s", (char *)UserCNMPMsg->Data1);
             PutA();
             break;
           case @{"CNMP_TEXTECHO" Link CNMP_TEXTECHO}:
             /*
              * CNMP_TEXTECHO - printable message sent from another
              * port!
              *
              * In this implementation, Var1 is being used as symbolic
              * of a PRIVATE message to another port.  This does NOT
              * have to be the case with all CNMP applications.  YOU,
              * the PROGRAMMER have the power to make it represent
              * whatever you wish.
              */
             if( UserCNMPMsg->@{"Var1" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} == TRUE )
               {
               /* PRIVATE MESSAGE to user - print handle and message */
               if(UserCNMPMsg->Data3)
                 {
                 /* handle recieved */
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "(%s) %s\n\0",
                                          (char *)UserCNMPMsg->Data3,
                                          (char *)UserCNMPMsg->Data1);
                 PutA();
                 }
               else
                 {
                 /* no handle received so print message only, no handle */
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "%s\n",
                                          (char *)UserCNMPMsg->Data1);
                 PutA();
                 }
               }
             else
               {
               /* PUBLIC MESSAGE - print handle and message */
               if(UserCNMPMsg->Data3)
                 {
                 /* handle recieved */
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, " %s: %s\n", (char *)UserCNMPMsg->Data3, (char *)UserCNMPMsg->Data1);
                 PutA();
                 }
               else
                 {
                 /* no handle received so print message only, no handle */
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "%s\n", (char *)UserCNMPMsg->Data1);
                 PutA();
                 }
               }
             break;
           case @{"CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM" Link CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM}:
             /*
              * CNet port UserCNMPMsg->FromPort has requested confirmation
              * that it may enter.
              *
              * Call the function PermitEntry(UserCNMPMsg) to allow
              * entry.
              *
              * Call the function RefuseEntry(UserCNMPMsg) to
              * refuse/disallow that port.
              *
              * This can be used to check a user's handle/account/access/etc..
              * before letting him/her enter.
              *
              * This test program will ALWAYS allow users in by never
              * checking anything and by always sending a CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT
              * message in reply via @{"PermitEntry()" Link PermitEntry()}.
              *
              * The first argument to PermitEntry() and @{"RefuseEntry()" Link RefuseEntry()}
              * MUST be a copy of the CNMP_ENTRYCONFIRM message that was
              * sent to request permission.
              *
              * The second argument to PermitEntry is a string that is
              * echo'd the remote user.  Simply pass an empty string ("")
              * if you don't want anything printed on the remote end
              */

             PermitEntry(UserCNMPMsg, "", MyCnmpCluster);
             break;
           case @{"CNMP_VARSINIT" Link CNMP_VARSINIT}:
             /* remote port sending it's data to us - don't forget to
              * send ours in return
              */

             /* find the port */
             if(TempRemotePort=PortFromMsg(UserCNMPMsg, MyCnmpCluster))
               {
               if(!TempRemotePort->PortVars)
                 {
                 /*
                  * port found - set the remote port data pointer
                  * if we don't already have it
                  */
                 TempRemotePort->PortVars = UserCNMPMsg->Data3;

                 /*
                  * give the remote port access to our declared
                  * variables also
                  */
                 sprintf(PortRange, "%d", TempRemotePort->PortNum);
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->FromPort = z->InPort;
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->CNMP_Type = CNMP_VARSINIT;
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data3 = MyCnmpCluster->cc_portvars;
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data2 = NULL;
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1 = NULL;
                 SendCNMPMessage(MyCnmpCluster, PortRange, MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg, FALSE, FALSE);
                 }
               }
             break;
           case @{"CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT" Link CNMP_ENTRYPERMIT}:
             if(PORTPERMISSION == 1)
               {
               /* print text if existent */
               if(UserCNMPMsg->Data1)
                  PutText((char *)UserCNMPMsg->Data1);

               /*
                * Permission allowed - Notify remote port that we have
                * entered!
                */
               sprintf(PortRange, "%d", UserCNMPMsg->FromPort);
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->FromPort = z->InPort;
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->CNMP_Type = CNMP_ADDPORT;
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1 = NULL;
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data2 = NULL;
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data3 = NULL;
               SendCNMPMessage(MyCnmpCluster, PortRange, MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg, FALSE, FALSE);

               /*
                * give the remote port(s) access to our declared
                * variables
                */
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->CNMP_Type = CNMP_VARSINIT;
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data3 = MyCnmpCluster->cc_portvars;
               SendCNMPMessage(MyCnmpCluster, PortRange, MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg, FALSE, FALSE);
               }
             break;
           case CNMP_DISPLAY_TV:
             /*
              * we really don't need the @{"PortFromMsg()" Link PortFromMsg()} function called
              * below.
              * It is for example's sake only.  We could have printed
              * our testvar without it.  It was required in this case
              * because we are printing the CNet port number that the
              * message was received from and we don't know it until we
              * find the remote port.
              */
             if(TempRemotePort=PortFromMsg(UserCNMPMsg, MyCnmpCluster))
               {
               sprintf(z->ABuffer, "Remote Port %d wants us to display \"testvar\".  testvar=%d\n", TempRemotePort->PortNum, MyCnmpCluster->cc_portvars->testvar);
               PutA();
               }
             else
               {
               PutText("ERROR 601: Could not get port from message\n");
               }
             break;
           }

         /* note - due to the way CNMP(tm) is set up, it is okay for
          * CNMPorts to ignore message types.  Important ones are handled
          * by @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()}.  Message that you don't use will be disposed of
          * anyways, at this point, by @{"DisposeCNMPMsg()" Link DisposeCNMPMsg()}.  If you want to
          * trap/handle any message types that you have added or #defined
          * yourself, add them - here - before your @{"DisposeCNMPMsg()" Link DisposeCNMPMsg()} call.
          *
          * REMEMBER!!: FOR EVERY @{"GetCNMPMsg()" Link GetCNMPMsg()} that you do, you must do
          *             a DisposeCNMPMessage() !!
          */

         DisposeCNMPMsg(UserCNMPMsg, MyCnmpCluster);
         }
       }

     /*
      * Check if there is a pending keyboard event
      * here we are being redundant by check both the MsgMask AND
      * the actual z-KBx keyboard dequeue variables but this is only
      * an example so it's okay.. :)
      * Usually, only one or the other is required.
      */
     if( (MsgMask & UserKey_Event) || (z->KB1 != z->KB2) )
       {
       if( (z->KBuff[z->KB1] == 13) || (z->KBuff[z->KB1] == 8) )
         {
         /*
          * flushes the keyboard if the first character is <ENTER> or <DEL>
          * this behavious is required for the conference replacement
          * program.  Other applications may not need this behaviour.
          */
         KBFlush(z); /* CNMP Keyboard flush routine */
         }
       else
         {
         /*
          * there are keys (other than ENTER or DEL) waiting in the
          * keyboard buffer
          *
          * Keyboard handling section - user has pressed a key.  Use
          * EnterLine() or OneKey() to read it..
          */
         EnterLine(255, 2048, "> ");

         if(strlen(z->InBuffer))
           {
           if(!stricmp(z->InBuffer, "help"))
             {
             DoHelp();
             }
           else if(z->InBuffer[0] == 92)
             {
             /*
              * first character of user entered string is a backslash,
              * therefore, a conference command
              */

             if(!stricmp(z->InBuffer, "\\Quit"))
               {
               FreeUserMsgs(MyCnmpCluster);
               IgnoreMsgs=TRUE;
               done=TRUE;  /* flag done=TRUE so that program will exit */
               }
             else if(!strnicmp(z->InBuffer, "\\fg", 3))
               /*
                * change foreground color
                * this is another application defined routine for the
                * CNMP Conference replacement program.
                */
               {
               if(strlen(z->InBuffer+3) == 1)
                 {
                 switch(z->InBuffer[3])
                   {
                   case '0':
                   case '1':
                   case '2':
                   case '3':
                   case '4':
                   case '5':
                   case '6':
                   case '7':
                   case '8':
                   case '9':
                   case 'a':
                   case 'b':
                   case 'c':
                   case 'd':
                   case 'e':
                   case 'f':
                      MyFgColor = z->InBuffer[3];
                      break;
                   default:
                      sprintf(z->ABuffer,
                             "\nERROR 509: color value '%c' out of range.\n",
                             z->InBuffer[3]);
                      PutA();
                      break;
                   }
                 }
               else
                 {
                 PutText("ERROR 506: You must specify an single MCI color value from 0-E\n           (ie. 0 for \c0, 1 for \c1)\n\n");
                 }
               }
             else if(!stricmp(z->InBuffer, "\\list"))
               {
               DoHelp();
               }
             else if(!strnicmp(z->InBuffer, "\\kick", 5))
               {
               /*
                * NOTE: I am using \KICK to force the user OUT of the
                * P-File.  Normally, if you are using ROOMS/channels for
                * a conference, you would kick the user from the CURRENT
                * channel, not the whole conference program.
                */

               if(strlen(z->InBuffer+5))
                 {
                 strcpy(z->ABuffer, z->InBuffer+5);
                 if(CheckDigits(z->ABuffer)) /* CNMP routine to check
                                               if a string is ALL
                                               digits/numeric */
                   {
                   /* string is all digits */
                   z->uz[0] = atoi(z->ABuffer);
                   if(TempRemotePort = PortFromNum(z->uz[0], MyCnmpCluster))
                      {
                      KickUser(TempRemotePort);
                      }
                   }
                 else
                   {
                   /* assume string is a handle or name since it's not all digits */
                   if(TempRemotePort = PortFromName(z->ABuffer, MyCnmpCluster, myp))
                     {
                     /* Found the port */
                     KickUser(TempRemotePort);
                     }
                   }
                 }
               else
                 {
                 PutText("[ERROR 505]: You must specify a port or user name to kick\n\n");
                 }
               }
             else if(!stricmp(z->InBuffer, "\\cnmports"))
               {
               /*
                * List currently allocated ports with the same
                * CNMP "@{"BASENAME" Link BASENAME}"
                */
               if(MyCnmpCluster->cc_firstport)
                 {
                 PutText("\n## Handle                PortName\n== ===================== ========\n");
                 TempRemotePort=MyCnmpCluster->cc_firstport;
                 while(TempRemotePort)
                   {
                   sprintf(z->ABuffer, "%2d %-21.21s %s\n", TempRemotePort->PortNum, (TempRemotePort->PortVars) ? TempRemotePort->PortVars->z->user1.Handle : "Unknown", TempRemotePort->PortName);
                   PutA();
                   TempRemotePort=TempRemotePort->NextPort;
                   }
                 DoReturn();
                 }
               }
             else if(!strnicmp(z->InBuffer, "\\var++", 6))
               {
               /* just a test to demonstrate remote port variable alteration */
               z->uz[0] = atoi(z->InBuffer+6);
               if(TempRemotePort = PortFromNum(z->uz[0], MyCnmpCluster))
                 {
                 TempRemotePort->PortVars->testvar++;
   
                 /* here is an example of a user installed CNMP_Type
                  * this type simply tells the remote port to display the
                  * contents of it's PortVar variable testvar
                  * To add this user-installed CNMP_Type, we added a
                  * define.  Don't forget to add a handler for this message
                  * type to the routine that handles your CNMP_Types..
                  */
                 sprintf(PortRange, "%d", TempRemotePort->PortNum);
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->FromPort = z->InPort;
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->CNMP_Type = CNMP_DISPLAY_TV; /* TV = acronym for testvar */
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1 = NULL;
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data2 = NULL;
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data3 = NULL;
                 SendCNMPMessage(MyCnmpCluster,
                                                   PortRange,
                                                   MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg,
                                                   TRUE,
                                                   FALSE);
                 }
               }
             else if(!strnicmp(z->InBuffer, "\\VARSCHECK", 10))
               {
               /* check on the state of variables from port x */
               /* this is just an example                     */
   
               z->uz[0] = atoi(z->InBuffer+10);
               if(TempRemotePort = PortFromNum(z->uz[0], MyCnmpCluster))
                 {
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "z->uz[0]: %d\n", z->uz[0]);
                 PutA();
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "CNetPort: %d\n",
                                        TempRemotePort->PortVars->z->InPort);
                 PutA();
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "User    : %s\n",
                                  TempRemotePort->PortVars->z->user1.Handle);
                 PutA();
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "Account#: %d\n",
                                            TempRemotePort->PortVars->z->id);
   
                 MakeDate(&TempRemotePort->PortVars->z->user1.ConnectDate,
                                                                z->InBuffer);
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "Logon   : %s\n", z->InBuffer);
                 PutA();
                 
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "testvar : %d\n",
                                          TempRemotePort->PortVars->testvar);
                 PutA();
                 }
               else
                 {
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "Could not find port %d\n", z->uz[0]);
                 PutA();
                 }
               }
             else if(!stricmp(z->InBuffer, "\\CLS"))
               {
               /*
                * this is an example of a command affecting the local screen
                * only
                */
               PutText("f1");
               }
             else if(!stricmp(z->InBuffer, "\\CLSALL"))
               {
               /* this is an example of a command affecting all port screens */
               /* take care of our own screen first. */
               PutText("f1");
               /*
                * send text to other port(s) here - *remember: YOU decide
                * what the @{"VarX" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} and
                * @{"DataX" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} are going to represent
                */

               /*
                * I use Var1 as a "flag" and in the case of a @{"CNMP_TEXTECHO" Link CNMP_TEXTECHO}
                * message, it will always mean PRIVATE if TRUE,
                * PUBLIC/BROADCAST if FALSE
                */
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Var1 = FALSE;

               /*
                * I use Data1 for the pointer to the remote user's MESSAGE in
                * the case of CNMP_TEXTECHO messages
                */
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1 = "f1";

               /* 4 bytes long */
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1Len=4;

               /*
                * I use Data2 as a pointer to the remote user's HANDLE in the
                * case of CNMP_TEXTECHO messages
                */
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data2 = NULL;

               /* CNMP_Type sets the type of Message */
               MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->CNMP_Type = @{"CNMP_TEXTECHO" Link CNMP_TEXTECHO};

               /* Send this message to ALL known ports! */
               SendCNMPMessage(MyCnmpCluster, "ALL", MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg, TRUE, FALSE);
               }
             else if(!strnicmp(z->InBuffer, "\\msg", 4))
               {
               /*
                * application defined
                * Here we send a PRIVATE message to the requested port
                */
               if(!strlen(z->InBuffer+4))
                 {
                 PutText("\nYou must specify a port number if you wish to send a private message\n(ie. \\priv0)\n\n");
                 }
               else
                 {
                 strcpy(PortRange, z->InBuffer+4);
                 RemoveLeadingSpace(PortRange);
                 if(strlen(PortRange))
                   {
                   if(stricmp(PortRange, "ALL"))
                     {
                     /*
                      * user is not broadcasting..  Check for name or port
                      * number
                      */
                     if(CheckDigits(PortRange))
                       {
                       /* string is all digits */
                       z->uz[0] = atoi(PortRange);
                       if(TempRemotePort = PortFromNum(z->uz[0], MyCnmpCluster))
                         {
                         /* Found the port */
                         sprintf(PortRange, "%d", TempRemotePort->PortNum);
                         }
                       else
                         {
                         sprintf(z->ABuffer, "ERROR 507: %s not found\n\n", PortRange);
                         PutA();
                         PortRange[0]=0;
                         }
                       }
                     else
                       {
                       /*
                        * assume string is a handle or name since it's not all
                        * digits
                        */
                       if(TempRemotePort = PortFromName(PortRange, MyCnmpCluster, myp))
                         {
                         /* Found the port */
                         sprintf(PortRange, "%d", TempRemotePort->PortNum);
                         }
                       else
                         {
                         sprintf(z->ABuffer, "ERROR 508: %s not found\n\n", PortRange);
                         PutA();
                         PortRange[0]=0;
                         }
                       }
                     }
                   if(strlen(PortRange))
                     {
                     sprintf(z->ABuffer, "msg %s> ", PortRange);
                     EnterLine(70, 0, z->ABuffer);
                     if(strlen(z->InBuffer))
                       {
                       /*
                        * send text to other port here - *remember: YOU
                        * decide what the VarX and DataX are going to
                        * represent
                        */
                       MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Var1 = TRUE;
     
                       /*
                        * I use Var1 as a "flag" and in the case of a
                        * @{"CNMP_TEXTECHO" Link CNMP_TEXTECHO} message, it will always
                        * mean PRIVATE if TRUE, PUBLIC/BROADCAST if FALSE
                        */
                       sprintf(z->ABuffer, "z%cc%c%s", MyBgColor, MyFgColor, z->InBuffer);
                       MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1Len = sizeof(UBYTE)*strlen(z->ABuffer)+1;

                       /*
                        * I use Data1 for the pointer to the remote user's
                        * MESSAGE in the case of CNMP_TEXTECHO messages
                        */
                       MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1 = z->ABuffer;

                       /*
                        * I use Data3 as a pointer to the remote user's HANDLE
                        * in the case of CNMP_TEXTECHO messages
                        */
                       MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data3 = &z->user1.Handle;

                       /* CNMP_Type sets the type of Message */
                       MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->CNMP_Type = @{"CNMP_TEXTECHO" Link CNMP_TEXTECHO};

                       /* Send this message only to the user specified port! */
                       SendCNMPMessage(MyCnmpCluster, PortRange, MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg, TRUE, FALSE);
                       }
                     }
                   }
                 }
               }
             else
               {
               strcpy(z->InBuffer, z->InBuffer + 1);
               if(!CommonCommands())
                 {
                 PutText("\nEnter \"\LIST\" for a summary of commands\n\n");
                 }
               else
                 {
                 PutText("\n");
                 }
               }
             }
           else
             {
             /*
              * send text to other port here - remember: YOU decide what the
              * VarX and DataX are going to represent
              * I chose them to represent what I needed them to be applied to
              * for this mini conference set-up..
              * p.s. the character 8 check below is a backspace trap.
              */
             if(strlen(z->InBuffer))
               {
               if(z->InBuffer[0] == 8)
                 {
                 DoReturn();
                 }
               else
                 {
                 sprintf(z->ABuffer, "z%cc%c%s", MyBgColor, MyFgColor, z->InBuffer);
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1Len = sizeof(UBYTE)*strlen(z->ABuffer)+1;

                 /*
                  * I use Var1 as a "flag" and in the case of a
                  * @{"CNMP_TEXTECHO" Link CNMP_TEXTECHO} message, it will always
                  * mean PRIVATE if TRUE, PUBLIC/BROADCAST if FALSE
                  */
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Var1 = FALSE;

                 /*
                  * I use Data1 for the pointer to the remote user's MESSAGE
                  * in the case of CNMP_TEXTECHO messages
                  */
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data1 = z->ABuffer;
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data2 = NULL;

                 /*
                  * I use Data3 as a pointer to the remote user's HANDLE in
                  * the case of CNMP_TEXTECHO messages
                  */
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->Data3 = &z->user1.Handle;

                 /* CNMP_Type sets the type of Message */
                 MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg->CNMP_Type = @{"CNMP_TEXTECHO" Link CNMP_TEXTECHO};

                 /* Send this message to ALL known ports! */
                 SendCNMPMessage(MyCnmpCluster, "ALL", MyCnmpCluster->cc_cnmpmsg, TRUE, FALSE);
                 }
               }
             }
           }
         }
       }
     if(MsgMask & UserTimer_Event)
       {
       /* Do other processing here. Anything that requires periodic
          checking/processing can be done here */
       /* This timeout message occurs approximately every 3/8 seconds */

       /* NOTE: Cnet seems to only check OLMs at PROMPTS (ie. EnterLine())
        * So you will have to check z->OLMWaiting to see if an OLM exists..
        * Also, the only place CNet allows an OLM to be displayed is at a
        * prompt.  ie.  During EnterLine().  OLMs will not appear unless
        * you call EnterLine().  Thus, OLMs will not be displayed until
        * you require input from the user.
        */
       }
     CheckFlowControl();
     } /* end of while(!done) loop */

@ENDNODE
@NODE InitCNMP() "InitCNMP()"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   InitCNMP -- Initializes the CnmpCluster required by CNMP and also opens
               all required message ports and the timer.device.

@{b}  SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   Cluster = InitCNMP(CNetPortData, @{"BASENAME" Link BASENAME}, portvarsize)

   struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *InitCNMP(struct PortData *, char *, LONG)

@{b}  FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routine allocates memory for the CnmpCluster structure and calls
   the @{"CreateCNMPMsgPort()" Link CreateCNMPMsgPort()} function to open the required message ports
   required by CNMP.

@{b}  INPUTS@{ub}
   CnetPortData  - a pointer to the Portdata structure for the current
                   port.
   BASENAME      - string buffer that represents the BASENAME of the
                   current application.  Each seperate application coded
                   with CNMP must have a unique BASENAME to avoid conflicts
                   with other CNMP applications.
   portvarsize   - the size of the PortVar structure
                   ie. sizeof(struct @{"PortVars" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 17})

@{b}  RESULT@{ub}
   Cluster - pointer to an allocated, initialized CnmpCluster structure or
             NULL (0L) on fail.

@ENDNODE
@NODE CreateCNMPMsgPort() "CreateCNMPMsgPort"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   CreateCNMPMsgPort -- Opens a MsgPort to be used for CNMP communication

@{b}  SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   MessagePort = CreateCNMPMsgPort(PortName)

   struct MsgPort *CreateCNMPMsgPort(char *)

@{b}  FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routine creates a named Exec MsgPort initialized and ready for use
   and returns a pointer to that message port.

@{b}  RESULT@{ub}
   MessagePort - a pointer to the intialized Exec MsgPort.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PortFromMsg() "PortFromMsg"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   PortFromMsg -- finds and returns the CNMP @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111} that sent a message.

@{b}  SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   remoteport = PortFromMsg(cnmpmsg, cluster)

   struct @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111} *PortFromMsg(struct @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} *, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}  FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routine extracts information about a port from the specified CNMPMsg
   and returns a pointer to the RemotePort structure that was opened by
   that port.

@{b}  INPUTS@{ub}
   cnmpmsg - a @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} that was received from a remote port
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}  RESULT@{ub}
   remoteport - a pointer to the RemotePort structure of the port that sent
                the message.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PortFromNum() "PortFromNum"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   PortFromNum -- finds and returns the port specified by the given CNet port
                  number.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   remoteport = PortFromNum(portnum, cluster)

   struct @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111} *PortFromNum(short, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routine accepts a CNet port number and returns a pointer to the
   RemotePort opened for that Cnet port.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   portnum - The CNet port number of the port you wish to find.
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   remoteport - a pointer to the RemotePort structure of the port that sent
                the message.

@ENDNODE
@NODE PortFromName() "PortFromName"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   PortFromName -- find and returns the port specified by the given username
                   or handle.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   remoteport = PortFromName(username, cluster)

   struct @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111} *PortFromName(char *, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routine accepts a user's name or handle and returns a pointer to
   the CNMP message port that is presently open on his CNet port.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   username - a user handle or name
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   remoteport - a pointer to the RemotePort that resides on the specified
   user's CNet port.


@ENDNODE
@NODE GetCNMPMsg() "GetCNMPMsg"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   GetCNMPMsg -- Gets the next queued CNMP message.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   cnmpmsg = GetCNMPMsg(fromport, cluster)

   struct @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} *GetCNMPMsg(LONG, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125})

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routine gets the first queued message of type CNMPMsg from a given
   port.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   fromport - a specific CNet port number or -1 if you want the next
              queued message regardless of the port number.
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   cnmpmsg - a pointer to the CNMPMsg.

@ENDNODE
@NODE GetNTReplyMsg() "GetNTReplyMsg"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   GetNTReplyMsg -- Gets the next queued CNMP message of type NT_ReplyMsg.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   cnmpmsg = GetNTReplyMsg(fromport, cluster)

   struct @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} *GetNTReplyMsg(LONG, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125})

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routine gets the first queued message of type CNMPMsg that is also
   tagged as NT_ReplyMsg from a given port.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   fromport - a specific CNet port number or -1 if you want the next
              queued NT_ReplyMsg message regardless of the port number.
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   cnmpmsg - a pointer to the CNMPMsg.

@ENDNODE
@NODE FindCNMPorts() "FindCNMPorts"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   FindCNMPorts -- Finds and creates a list of all currently active CNMP
                   ports that have the same BASENAME.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   FindCNMPorts(baseport,cluster)

   void FindCNMPorts(char *, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125})

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routines finds all remote CNMP ports that share a common @{"BASENAME" Link BASENAME}.
   As it finds other CNMP ports, it adds them to a CNMP maintained list of
   currently valid CNMP ports.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   @{"BASENAME" Link BASENAME} - the same basename that was used to in the @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}
              call, used to initialize your CNMP port.
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by InitCNMP()

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   none

@ENDNODE
@NODE SetTimeout() "SetTimeout"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   SetTimeout -- Posts a time request of x seconds and y micros.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   success = SetTimeout(seconds, mics, cluster)

   BOOL SetTimeout(LONG, LONG, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125})

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This routines aborts any previously posted time requests and posts a new
   time request with a timeout of x seconds and y micros. This is VERY important if you
   wish to call @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()} and want it to return after 5/8 seconds even if
   there is no Arexx message or Remote port messages waiting.  This is a
   very useful feature of CNMP as it allows your program to do other
   processing before calling @{"HandleIO" Link HandleIO()} again to wait for more messages or
   another timeout.

   NOTE:  The seconds and micrs values are summed to produce a single time
          request of x seconds and y micros.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   seconds - the number of seconds to wait before returning a @{"UserTimer_Event" Link UserTimer_Event}.
   mics    - the number of micros to wait beore returning a @{"UserTimer_Event" Link UserTimer_Event}
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   TRUE is the time request was succesfully posted, FALSE if an error occured.

@ENDNODE
@NODE CleanupTimeout() "CleanupTimeout"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   CleanupTimeout -- Aborts a previously posted timer request.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   CleanupTimeout(cluster)

   void CleanupTimout(struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125})

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This function aborts any previously posted CNMP time request.  Use this
   abort time requests before exiting your application.  This function is
   already called by the GetOut() function in the CNMPempty.c source file
   that accompanies the CNMP package.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   none

@ENDNODE
@NODE CheckCNMPExists() "CheckCNMPExists"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   CheckCNMPExists -- This function accepts a CNet port number and returns a
                      pointer to the CNMPort that is open on that CNet port.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   remoteport = CheckCNMPExists(portnum, cluster)

   struct @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111} *CheckCNMPExists(int, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This function accepts a CNet port number and returns a pointer to the
   CNMPort that is open on that CNet port.
   This function differs from @{"PortFromNum()" Link PortFromNum()} in that this routine checks the
   actual validity of the port itself whereas PortFromNum() simply checks the
   local port list.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   portnum  - the CNet port number of the CNMPort you wish to find or check.
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   remoteport - a pointer to the CNMPort that is open on the given CNet port.

@ENDNODE
@NODE SendCNMPMessage() "SendCNMPMessage"

@{b}  NAME@{ub}
   SendCNMPMessage -- sends the a CNMPMsg to a remote port.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   success = SendCNMPMessage(cluster, portnum, message, echolocal, overridecheck)

   BOOL SendCNMPMessage(struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *, char *, struct @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} *, BOOL, BOOL)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   Sends a properly filled CNMPMsg to the desired remote CNet port number.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   cluster       - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}
   portnum       - an ASCII representation of the CNet port number you wish your
                   message to be sent to.  "ALL" may be subsituted if you wish to
                   BROADCAST the message to all presently valid CNMP @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111}s
                   that share the same BASEPORT name.
   message       - a pointer to a filled out @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} structure.
   echolocal     - set TRUE if you wish this message to be sent to your own
                   port.  set FALSE if you wish this message to be send to only
                   remote ports.
   overridecheck - SendCNMPMessage has an internal sanity check that checks
                   if the remote port is in the LOCAL port list.  In some
                   instances this may not be desired, as in the case of a
                   port that has just entered it's CNMP process and has
                   not yet been added to the local port list.  Set
                   overridecheck = TRUE or 1 if you wish SendCNMPMessage to
                   bypass it's internal validity check.

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   success - TRUE is message was successfully sent.  FALSE if error.
             NOTE: Broadcast messages (messages addressed to "ALL" ports) will
                   always return TRUE.

@ENDNODE
@NODE FreeCNMPList() "FreeCNMPList()"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   FreeCNMPList -- Frees the memory used for the local port list.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   FreeCNMPList(cluster)

   void FreeCNMPList( struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} * )

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This function frees all memory used to hold the list of remote ports
   that was created by @{"FindCNMPPorts()" Link FindCNMPorts()}, therefore making the list empty.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   cluster       - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   none

@ENDNODE
@NODE CNMPortToList() "CNMPortToList"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   CNMPortToList -- Adds the specified CNet Port number with the specified
                    CNMP port name to the list of local @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111}s.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   firstport = CNMPortToList(cluster, portnum, portname)

   struct @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111} *CNMPortToList(struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *, int, char *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   This function adds the specified CNet Port number with the specified CNMP
   port name to the list of local RemotePorts.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   cluster  - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}
   portnum  - the CNet port number of the CNMP port to add
   portname - the name of the RemotePort to add to the local port list.

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   firstport - always returns a pointer to the first RemotePort in the
               local list.

@ENDNODE
@NODE NotifyCNMPRemove() "NotifyCNMPRemove"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   NotifyCNMPRemove -- notifies all other ports in the local port list that
                       the current port is exiting/quitting.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   NotifyCNMPRemove(cluster)

   void NotifyCNMPRemove(struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   notifies all other ports in the local port list that the current port is
   exiting/quitting. This causes the remote ports to remove this port from
   their local port list(s).

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   cluster  - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

   RESULTS
   none

@ENDNODE
@NODE CarrierCheck() "CarrierCheck"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   CarrierCheck -- Checks the current CNet port for lost/dropped carrier, user
                   time up and dumped user.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   carrier = CarrierCheck(z)

   BOOL CarrierCheck(struct PortData *z)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   Checks the current CNet port for lost/dropped carrier, user time up and
   dumped user.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   z - a pointer to the PortData structure of the local CNet port.

   RESULTS
   carrier = TRUE if carrier is present, FALSE if no carrier.

@ENDNODE
@NODE KBFlush() "KBFlush"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   KBFlush -- Flushes the keyboard buffer of the local CNet port.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   KBFlush(portdata)

   void KBFlush(struct PortData *z)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   Flushes the keyboard buffer of the local CNet port. (thanks to Bob Maple
   [The Brazilian] for this code from over a year ago.. :)

   Since this code was not my own (even though it's a single, simple line of
   code), here it is in case you may need it for other projects:

      z->KB1=z->KB2=0;


@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   z - a pointer to the PortData structure of the local CNet port.

   RESULTS
   none

@ENDNODE
@NODE HandleIO() "HandleIO"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   HandleIO -- Handles receipt and processing/storing of messages from remote
               CNMP ports.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   returnmask = HandleIO(rexxcontext, cluster)

   LONG HandleIO(ULONG, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   Handles receipt and processing/storing of messages from remote CNMP ports.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   rexxcontext - the signal mask of the ARexx user port. I use EasyRexx in
                 the example CNMPConf.c because it is very easy to implement
                 for even the most inexperienced C coders.  If you use
                 EasyRexx in your applcation, simply specify the following
                 as rexxcontext:

                     ER_SIGNAL(RexxContext)

   cluster  - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   returnmask - a set of OR'd signal bits representing the types of messages
                returned.  Be sure to test the returnmask for ALL bits that
                you are expecting as more than one bit may be returned set
                in the returnmask.

@ENDNODE
@NODE FileUserMsg() "FileUserMsg"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   FileUserMsg -- Stores the specified message in the local list of saved
                  messages from other ports.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   firstmessage = FileUserMsg(usermessage, cluster)

   struct @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} *FileUserMsg(struct CNMPMsg *, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   Stores the specified message in the local list of saved messages from other
   ports.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   usermessage - a message of type CNMPMsg that is to be added to the local
                 list of saved messages.
   cluster     - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   firstmessage - a pointer to the first message in the local list of saved
                  messages

@ENDNODE
@NODE FreeUserMsgs() "FreeUserMsgs"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   FreeUserMsgs -- Deletes all messages in the saved local list of messages
                   and frees all memory that was required to save them.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   FreeUserMsgs(cluster)

   void FreeUserMsgs(struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   Deletes all messages in the local list of saved messages and frees all
   memory that was required to hold them. 

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   none

@ENDNODE
@NODE DisposeCNMPMsg() "DisposeCNMPMsg"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   DisposeCNMPMsg -- Removes the specified message from the local list of saved
                     messages and frees the memory that was set aside for it.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   DisposeCNMPMsg(message, cluster)

   void DisposeCNMPMsg( struct @{"CNMPMsg" Link include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main 30} *, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   Removes the specified message from the local list of saved messages and
   frees the memory that was set aside for it.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   message - a pointer to the message that is to be disposed of/killed.
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   none


@ENDNODE
@NODE DisposeCNMPType() "DisposeCNMPType"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   DisposeCNMPType -- Disposes messages of a given CNMP_Type that were
                      received from the specified remote port.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   success = DisposeCNMPType(msgtype, portnum, cluster)

   BOOL DisposeCNMPType(LONG, LONG, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125})

@{b}   FUNCTION@{ub}
   Scans the saved list of remote messages and disposes messages of a given
   CNMP_Type that were received from the specified remote port.

@{b}   INPUTS@{ub}
   msgtype - the CNMP_Type that you wish to dispose of.
   portnum - the CNet port number from which the messages to be disposed
             of originated.
   cluster - the CnmpCluster that was initialized and returned by @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   success - TRUE if one or more messages were killed, FALSE if none were
             disposed of.

@ENDNODE
@NODE RemoveCNMPortList() "RemoveCNMPortList"

@{b}   NAME@{ub}
   RemoveCNMPortList -- Removes the specified port from the local list of
                        ports.

@{b}   SYNOPSIS@{ub}
   success = RemoveCNMPortList(remport, cluster)

   BOOL RemoveCNMPortList(struct @{"RemotePort" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 111} *, struct @{"CnmpCluster" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 125} *)

