                 ie. sizeof(struct @{"PortVars" Link "include:cnmp/cnmp.h/Main" 17})

@{b}   RESULT@{ub}
   none

@ENDNODE
@NODE HandleRexx() "HandleRexx"

   If you are using the included EasyRexx ((C) 1994,1995, Ketil Hunn),
HandleRexx() (or something similar) is the function you will use to handle
Arexx messages.  Here is a sample HandleRexx function with some simple Arexx
commands and their handler functions:


/**************************************************************************
 * This function not part of CNMP - this IS required for EasyRexx
 **************************************************************************/
void HandleRexx( void )
{
	UBYTE ResultString[255];
	LONG ResultLong=0;

	if(GetARexxMsg(RexxContext))
		{
		switch(RexxContext->id)
			{
			case AREXX_QUIT:
				/* received quit message from ARexx */
				ReplyARexxMsg(RexxContext, TAG_DONE);
				GetOut("", 0);
				break;
			case AREXX_TEXTECHO:
				/* Recieved a message from ARexx to echo/print some text */
				sprintf(z->ABuffer, "z4c6AREXX_MSG:q1 %s\n", ARGSTRING(RexxContext, 0));
				PutA();
				break;
			case AREXX_VERSION:
				/* received a message from ARexx to print the version number */
				sprintf(ResultString, "%s", vers+5);
				break;
			case AREXX_INC_TV:
				/* received a message from ARexx to increment this port's testvar variable */
				MyCnmpCluster->cc_portvars->testvar += ARGNUMBER(RexxContext, 0);
				break;
			case AREXX_SHOW_TV:
				/* received a message from ARexx to display this port's testvar variable */
				sprintf(z->ABuffer, "** Arexx asked us to display testvar:  testvar=%d\n", MyCnmpCluster->cc_portvars->testvar);
				PutA();
				break;
			case AREXX_QUERY_TV:
				/* received a message from ARexx to return this port's testvar variable */
				ResultLong=MyCnmpCluster->cc_portvars->testvar;
				break;
			}
		if(strlen(ResultString))
			ReplyARexxMsg(RexxContext, ER_ResultString, ResultString, TAG_DONE);
		else if(ResultLong)
			ReplyARexxMsg(RexxContext, ER_ResultLong, ResultLong, TAG_DONE);
		else
			ReplyARexxMsg(RexxContext, TAG_DONE);
		}
}

@ENDNODE
@NODE BASENAME "BASENAME"

   BASENAME
   The CNMP BASENAME is a string of text that serves as an "identifier" for
   the set of shared message ports that a particular application uses.  Each
   application must have a unique BASENAME so that it does not conflict with
   other CNMP applications.  For example, a chat program written by MetalSoft
   may use a BASENAME of "MS-CHAT" or "chat23A5" where a CNet Help Bot may
   have a BASENAME of "BOT45X2".  The BASENAME is what CNMP uses to name and
   find other ports that are using the same application.  Each CNMP Message
   Port is named BASENAMEx where x = the CNet port number on which the
   application is running.

NOTE: YOU set the BASENAME that your application will use when you call the
      function @{"InitCNMP()" Link InitCNMP()}.

MetalSoft will be keeping a list of BASENAMEs currently in use by registered
CNMP developers. To get a list, simply contact us using any of the methods
outlined in the section describing registration procedures.

@ENDNODE
