@NODE ArexxContext "Context Numbers"

   NAME
   Context Numbers

   FUNCTION
   Context numbers are integers defined as a signal of which Arexx command
   was received from an ARexx script.  Each Context number must be unique
   from other context numbers used in the application.  Context numbers work
   hand in hand with the @{"ARexxCommandTable" Link ARexxCommandTable} to allow easy implementation of
   ARexx to your application/program.

   If you want to #define your own ARexx commands for CNMP applications,
   please start numbering them at 500 to retain compatibility with future
   versions of CNMP.


   EXAMPLES
   #define AREXX_QUIT                1
   #define AREXX_VERSION             2
   #define YOUR_AREXX_COMMAND        500
   #define YOUR_SECOND_AREXX_COMMAND 501

@ENDNODE
@NODE ARexxCommandTable "ArexxCommandTable"

   NAME
   ARexxCommandTable

   FUNCTION
   The ARexxCommandTable is a lookup table for EasyRexx.  The command table
   is an array of ARexxCommandTable structures, each defining a single ARexx
   command that your application will support. The structure is laid out as
   follows:


         ContextNumber, "Rexx_Command",   "ArgString",   UserData


    - the first element of the command table is the @{"ContextNumber" Link ContextNumber} of the
      Arexx command.

    - the second element of the command table is the actual ARexx command
      that will be used in ARexx scripts.

    - the third element of the command table is a string that describes the
      argument(s) that the ARexx command will accept.
 
    - the fourth element of the command table is tagged as "UserData" which,
      for CNMP, is not explicitly used. Feel free, however, to take advantage
      of advanced C techniques by placing a function pointer there and alter
      @{"HandleRexx()" Link HandleRexx()} to pass control to that function.  For the sake of novices,
      we will stick to the easy stuff throughout this document.


      From @{"EasyRexxGuide" link "EasyRexxGuide/Main"} by Ketil Hunn:
      =============================================
      When easyrexx.library receives an AREXX command  that matches a command
      in the command table, it will parse  the arguments according to the
      template.

      If the arguments do not match or are too few it will reply the message
      with an error and your application will never hear the message.

      If success, your application will  receive  the command with all
      arguments stuffed in an array with the first argument in 0, second in 1
      etc.

      Useful macros to get ARexx arguments:
      ARGSTRING(context, i) - returns the string in argument i.
      ARGNUMBER(context, i) - returns the number in argument i.
      ARG(context, i)       - returns 0 if the argument  is NULL and non-zero if
                              it present.
      ARGBOOL(context,i)    - returns TRUE if  the  argument  is  not  empty and
                              FALSE if it is.

      Defining templates
      Options in the template are separated  by  commas.   To get the results
      of EasyRexx message, you examine the array of longwords you passed to it
      (one entry per option in the template).  Exactly  what  is put in a
      given entry depends on the type of option.   The  default  is  a string
      (a sequence of non-whitespace characters, or delimited by quotes, which
      will be stripped, in which case the entry will be a pointer.

      Options can be followed by  modifiers,  which  specify  things such as
      the type of the option.  Modifiers are  specified by following the
      option with a / and a single character  modifier.  Multiple modifiers
      can be specified by using multiple /s.  Valid modifiers are:

      /S -  Switch.  This is considered a boolean  variable,  and will be set
                     if the option name appears in the command-line. The entry
                     is the boolean (0 for not set, non-zero for set).

      /K -  Keyword. This means that the option  will  not be filled unless
                     the keyword appears. For example if the template is
                     "Name/K", then unless "Name=<string>" or "Name <string>"
                     appears in the command line, Name will not be filled.

      /N -  Number.  This parameter is considered a decimal number. If an
                     invalid number is specified, an  error will be returned.
                     The entry will be a pointer to the longword number
                     (this is how you know if a number was specified).

      /T -  Toggle.  This is similar to a  switch, but when specified causes
                     the boolean value to "toggle".  Similar to /S.

      /A - Required. This keyword must be given a value during command-line
                     processing, or an error is returned.

      /F -  line.    If this is specified, the entire rest of the line is
                     taken as the parameter for the option, even if other
                     option keywords appear in it.

      /M -  strings. This means the argument will take any number of strings,
                     returning them as an array of strings. Any arguments not
                     considered to be  part  of another option will be added
                     to this option. Only one /M should be specified in a
                     template. Example for a template "Dir/M,All/S" the
                     command-line "foo bar all qwe" will set the boolean
                     "all", and return  an  array consisting of "foo", "bar",
                     and "qwe". The entry in the array will  be a pointer to
                     an array of string pointers, the last of which will be
                     NULL.

   There is an interaction between /M  parameters and /A parameters. If there
   are unfilled /A parameters after  parsing,  it  will grab strings from the
   end of a previous /M parameter  list  to  fill  the /As.  This is used for
   things like Copy ("From/A/M,To/A").
   ======= END OF EasyRexxGuide segment =========


      Here is an example ARexxCommandTable:

      struct ARexxCommandTable rxtbl[] =
      	{
      	AREXX_QUIT,			"CNMPQUIT",		 NULL,			NULL,
      	AREXX_TEXTECHO,	"CNMPECHO",     "STRING/F",	NULL,
      	AREXX_VERSION,		"CNMPVER",	    NULL,			NULL,
      	AREXX_INC_TV,		"CNMPVARINC",	 "AMOUNT/N",	NULL,
      	AREXX_QUERY_TV,	"CNMPVARQUERY", NULL,			NULL,
      	AREXX_SHOW_TV,		"CNMPVARSHOW",  NULL,         NULL,
      	TABLE_END,
	};

   See @{"HandleRexx" Link HandleRexx()} for the function that handles
   these ARexx commands.  Also see @{"EasyRexxGuide" link "EasyRexxGuide/Main"} for more info

@ENDNODE
@NODE compiling "compiling/linking"

   Compiling and linking your CNMP program
   =======================================

   To compile and link your CNMP program on a single line, you use the same
   compile command as usual, but with two additions:

      link lib=lib:cnmp.o lib=lib:easyrexx.lib

   The command I use to compile AND LINK CNMP applications in one command is:

      sc <sourcename.c> GST=/cnh/i GSTIMM LIB=lib:cres.o lib=LIB:cnmp.o lib=lib:EasyRexx.lib PARMS=REG NOSTKCHK CPU=ANY COMNEST STRMERGE verbose link

   To compile without linking:

      sc <sourcename.c> GST=/cnh/i GSTIMM PARMS=REG NOSTKCHK CPU=ANY COMNEST STRMERGE verbose

   To link:

      slink FROM LIB:c.o "sourcename.o"+"lib:CNMP.o" TO <ProgName> LIB lib:cres.o LIB:sc.lib LIB:amiga.lib LIB:easyrexx.lib VERBOSE NOICONS

@ENDNODE
